Subsidy trap
Cambridge, United States—No other policy so directly pits good economics against good politics as food and energy subsidies.
Unaffordable subsidies have become a core issue for three of the world's most important new leaders: Egyptian President Abdel Fattah el-Sisi, Indonesian President Joko “Jokowi” Widodo, and Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi.
The reduction in subsidies that Xi Xi faces needs to be somewhat better than anticipated.
On the contrary, Modi faces a situation that is even worse than anticipated, and there is even a possibility of undermining the eagerly awaited World Trade Organization agreement.
The situation facing Joko Widodo is still unclear.
In July, Xi Xi achieved what few leaders in North Africa and the Middle East have managed to do: he significantly reduced long-standing energy subsidies, raising prices by 41-78%.
It is surprising that there was almost no opposition to the protests.
The food subsidy program in Egypt consumes over $5 billion annually and urgently needs reform.
The price of bread has remained at an extremely low level, often being used to feed animals.
In the past, efforts by North African countries to reduce such subsidies have often sparked unrest and even led to government overthrow.
