The bread subsidy has been cut by 13%.
Xi Xi had no choice.
Even after reducing subsidies, the incumbent government’s budget deficit target for the next fiscal year still amounts to 10% of GDP (it would be 14% without the subsidy cuts).
However, few anticipated that Sitthi would be able to act more swiftly than Modi in the tumultuous political environment. Modi secured the prime ministership in India, where there was a strong desire for thorough economic reform, with an overwhelming democratic majority.
In Indonesia, Joko Widodo, who took office in October, inherits fuel subsidies that amount to as much as $21 billion per year (equivalent to 20% of government spending) and have already put a strain on the nation.
Suharto, who stepped down a year ago, had already taken a brave first step by raising fuel prices.
The advisors to Joko Widodo suggested cutting the remaining subsidies, and he frankly indicated that he plans to phase in the implementation over four years.
Economists are confident in opposing subsidies for commodities because agricultural and energy markets approach perfect competition, with large numbers of consumers on the demand side and large numbers of producers on the supply side.
In areas where competition is imperfect, it is government—not large private monopolies—that is the remedy.
Critics of the invisible hand argue that self-regulating private markets may fail in various ways.
For example, income inequality and environmental externalities are the two main reasons for government intervention.
What makes debates over food and fossil fuel subsidies particularly contentious is that they are often justified under the banners of environmental or social equity goals, yet in practice they tend to be counterproductive to those very objectives, often achieving the opposite effect.
Only about 20% of Egyptian food subsidies go to the poor.
Gas subsidies in most countries fatten the middle class, while the poor rely on walking or public transportation.
In India, less than 0.1% of liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) subsidies go to the poorest of the poor, while 52.6% flow into the pockets of the richest.
Only less than 20% of fossil fuel subsidies go to the poorest 20% of the population worldwide.
Food and energy subsidies also risk distorting public policy, and the Modi government, which seeks to protect agricultural subsidies in India, serves as a prime example.
In fact, the Modi government rejected compromise deals at the World Trade Organization, which had the effect of destroying the most significant progress of multilateral trade negotiations over the past decade.
Agricultural subsidies sometimes benefit producers at the expense of consumers, especially in poor countries; and at other times benefit consumers at the expense of producers, especially in rich countries.
The policy in India aims to have both.
As a result, India accomplished a feat: it allocated wheat to consumers at below-human prices while experiencing an over-supply, as farmers could get higher prices.
(Farmers receive subsidies for agricultural inputs such as electricity, water, and fertilizer, while the environment suffers.)
(The government acquired vast amounts of corrupt rice and wheat, but distributed only a small portion of it in a manner that was both corrupt and failed to help the poor.)
The government may continue to maintain subsidies and storage programs.
But it knows that this would violate WTO rules.
Since he could not permanently change these rules, Modi scrapped the Trade Facilitation Agreement, which the WTO had eagerly anticipated.
Once the subsidies are implemented, it is difficult to retract them.
When world commodity prices rise (as they have over the past decade), citizens accustomed to domestic prices determined by the market are more likely to accept the reality that officials cannot insulate them from the shock.
But people accustomed to officially set food and energy prices will demand that the government take responsibility.
This constitutes a strong reason why subsidies should not have been implemented from the start.
But this does not mean that maintaining the subsidy will necessarily be the wisest choice for astute politicians once the subsidy is implemented.
If the alternative to price increases is shortages or rationing, angry opponents could also erupt.
Similarly, if the growing disparities ultimately lead to higher retail prices, slow-moving leaders cannot expect to benefit either.
In an ideal scenario, while cutting food and energy subsidies, other more effective measures to support lower-income households should be implemented.
Developing countries have already gained significant experience in effective transfer mechanisms, such as innovative conditional cash transfer policies like Progresa-Oportunidades in Mexico and Bolsa Família in Brazil, as well as technological innovations like India's Unique Identification (UID) system.
But some countries only adjust their budgets in response to a crisis, and they may not have the money available for transfers to cushion the pain.
Shrewd politicians might best implement unpopular adjustments at the very beginning of their tenure.
Joko and Xi both adopted this approach.
And Modi, who won the election by a landslide under the slogan of market reforms, is now behind.
